subject: Generate 127.0.1.1 entry on each individual host
commit_message:
Generate 127.0.1.1 entry on each individual host

The hostfile update script is currently being generated on the
deployment host and copied to all other hosts within an environment.
This is resulting in the 127.0.1.1 entry always containing the hostname
of the deployment host.

Instead, generate a temporary file for the script locally which
pre-populates all shared hosts entries and use that as a template for
assigning the 127.0.1.1 entry on each remote host.

Change-Id: Ia5e375772cab76c748cca058ae7d7944e7528020
Closes-Bug: #1657568
(cherry picked from commit a436640aa7f51dd244be2b34773ff3c0bd04b296)

subject: Code-Defined Resource-specific Options
commit_message:
Code-Defined Resource-specific Options

Implement the code-defined resource specific options framework
for the Identity subsystem (User). Options are defined in code
in the keystone.identity.backends.resource_options. These options
are extracted from the update dict, validated for a specific type,
and stored in an attribute association (as a one[User] to
Many[one-per-option-type]) relation in a database table.

On retrival options are converted from the association to elements
in the user reference dict.

Setting an option explicitly to None removes the option (unsets it).

Updating a specific option will have no impact on other options.

Change-Id: I90875ce2c3cf899557bb1f215fa1bda9576cbe83

will attach to the interface created using other means.

Closes-Bug: #1602798
Change-Id: Ieab92bde48742d6e174017c56d29adde9533538a

subject: adds support for vhost user reconnect.
commit_message:
adds support for vhost user reconnect.

- vhost-user reconnect is a new feature added
  in dpdk 16.07 and qemu 2.7.
- vhost-user reconnect allows VMs using vhost-user
  interfaces to reconnect to the vhost-user backend if
  the backend terminates either as a result of a graceful
  shutdown or a crash with out requiring the vm to reboot.
- vhost-user reconnect requires qemu to be the vhost-user server
  and ovs to be the client.
- dpdk prior to 16.07 only supports qemu client/ dpdk server mode.
- This change extends the ovs mech driver to select the correct qemu
  vhost user socket mode based on the available interface types
  reported by the agent.

Change-Id: Iec89eaa597311e086c5f6e8d67308d446b07ac33
Closes-Bug: #1604924
Depends-on: Ia5da5b3ef28d1b23b217adc5196199df47b54ed9

The change 916cfaf "Introduce encryption provider constants"
intended to issue deprecation messages for encryptors that
are no longer going to be supported in Pike, and continue
loading the current os_brick encryptors instead.

However, since it removed the "'LuksEncryptor' in provider"
style checks, any config values that were not explicitly listed
in LEGACY_PROVIDER_CLASS_TO_FORMAT_MAP will not be translated.

This results in a configuration using a provider of
"nova.volume.encryptors.luks.LuksEncryptor" to attempt to
import this module directly into Cinder when previously it
would use the os_brick encryptor.  This is generally wrong
and causes a number of problems.

Closes-Bug: #1658755

Change-Id: I3ec6e3fe919bc03d158da04a18fb8b651002ed52

subject: Use new network for each subnet scenario run
commit_message:
Use new network for each subnet scenario run

Using _get_or_create_network was resulting in all concurrent
runners creating/updating/deleting subnets on a single Neutron
network. This was problematic for two reasons.

First, a network in Neutron in any normal deployment does not
have that many concurrent subnet create/update/deletes happening
on it at once because networks very rarely have more than 1 or 2
subnets on them.

Second, it made it appear as though Neutron was having
performance problems for handling lots of concurrent subnet
requests because Neutron internally performs overlapping checks
for subnets within a given network.

So we weren't getting performance measurements for normal heavy
usage (lots of subnet activity across lots of different networks)
and we were getting performance measurements for a non-standard
case (significant subnet activity within a single network).

This adjusts the scenario to always create a network for each
test run, which brings it inline with normal heavy use deployment
behavior.

Change-Id: I254dbd166a79ca07e18a61da92bc536b035452e1

subject: Use %i instead of %I in dhcp-interface@.service
commit_message:
Use %i instead of %I in dhcp-interface@.service

Per the bug report, %I results in -'s in the interface name being
replaced with /'s, which means when we try to look up the interface
by path in dhcp-all-interfaces.sh we end up at an invalid path.
Using %i instead should fix the problem.

See https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.unit.html

Essentially what is happening is that we start with a name like
br-ex that wasn't escaped in the first place.  However, because of
the - it looks like it could have been escaped to systemd.  When
we use %I, which tries to unescape escaped values, it unescapes a
value that was already not escaped.

Change-Id: I434ed2e084d4477dc7a2b7827164586f8ea0c1e3
Closes-Bug: 1649409

subject: Limit polling namespaces in API container
commit_message:
Limit polling namespaces in API container

Removes the "compute" polling namespace from the ceilometer-polling
agent inside the API container.

By default both the "compute" and "central" polling namespaces are
enabled [1], and the compute namespace requires libvirt to be
installed or else ceilometer-polling will fail to start [2]. Since
we are not hosting instances inside the API container, we can
disable the namespace.

[1]: https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/4108d6d2cbe2ae509ed532b0be5c0f7d405fd0d6/ceilometer/cmd/polling.py#L65
[2]: http://logs.openstack.org/22/391522/2/check/gate-openstack-ansible-openstack-ansible-aio-ubuntu-xenial/6837eba/logs/openstack/aio1_ceilometer_api_container-2218d6eb/ceilometer/ceilometer-polling.log.txt.gz

could have, which can cause these tests to have false positives
because there may be additional unexpected values in the metadata.

When using the 'groups' keyword in a federation mapping, the value
passed in the assertion map be a simple string with a space. For
example, "ALL USERS". This results in ast.literal_eval() raising
a SyntaxError and not ValueError, which bubbles up to the API as
an uncaught 500 Internal Server Error.

subject: De-duplicate properties_data between events, resources
commit_message:
De-duplicate properties_data between events, resources

Properties data (encrypted or not) is now stored in the
resource_properties_data table. We still support reading properties
data from the legacy locations (separate columns in the resource and
event tables) but all new properties data are written to
resource_properties_data.

Instead of duplicating properties data for a given resource
and its events, we refer to the same resource_properties_data
object from both resources and events.

Notes about encrypting/decrypting properties data:

1. ResourcePropertiesData takes care of encrypting/decrypting, so
   consumers (events and resources) don't have to worry about it.
2. Previously (not anymore), heat.engine.resource would take care of
   the encrypting in _store() and _store_or_update().
3. Previously and currently, heat.object.resource decrypts the legacy
   properties_data field if needed.

Change-Id: I569e16d4a7d3f5ccc22d57fe881c4fd5994677ac
Closes-Bug: #1524013

subject: Require placement-client service in Newton subnode during grenade
commit_message:
Require placement-client service in Newton subnode during grenade

The placement service is required before upgrading Nova to Ocata.
During a multi-node grenade run, the primary node is configured
for placement when upgrading from Newton to Ocata due to the
script in change I573149b9415da2a8bb3951a4c4ce71c4c3e48c6f.

However, grenade doesn't configure the subnode (Newton in this
case). So in the multi-node grenade job, the Newton subnode will
not be configured to connect to the placement API and therefore
won't register as a resource provider, and because of this and
change Ie12acb76ec5affba536c3c45fbb6de35d64aea1b, the Nova
filter scheduler won't consider that host available for building
instances.

Normally this is fine and we expect deployments to be doing rolling
upgrades of their computes when upgrading to Ocata and potentially
be under-utilized for placement, but in our CI system it causes
the multinode grenade job to fail the test_schedule_to_all_nodes
test in Tempest which uses availability zones to force instance
builds to the specific compute nodes in the multinode run, and since
the Newton subnode isn't checking in with placement, the scheduler
doesn't use it and the specific instance build for that node fails.

Change-Id: I143a59a2e50f1d3c76f0633a47212c0be8314a48

subject: Replace yaml.load() with yaml.safe_load()
commit_message:
Replace yaml.load() with yaml.safe_load()

Avoid dangerous file parsing and object serialization libraries.
yaml.load is the obvious function to use but it is dangerous[1]
Because yaml.load return Python object may be dangerous if you
receive a YAML document from an untrusted source such as the
Internet. The function yaml.safe_load limits this ability to
simple Python objects like integers or lists.

In addition, Bandit flags yaml.load() as security risk so replace
all occurrences with yaml.safe_load(). Thus I replace yaml.load()
with yaml.safe_load()

[1]https://security.openstack.org/guidelines/dg_avoid-dangerous-input-parsing-libraries.html

Change-Id: Id83e2a28355ba09cf22ea4e422de9b39e4f03c5e

subject: Fix ci gate deploy multiple k8s slave
commit_message:
Fix ci gate deploy multiple k8s slave

In ceph-multi gate, only one k8s slave can be installed, as
stdin is eated by ssh, use `-n` option to prevent it.

e.g.

$ cat test
111
222

$ cat test | while read line; do
>     echo $line
>     ssh 127.0.0.1 "hostname" >/dev/null 2>&1
> done
111

$ cat test | while read line; do
>     echo $line
>     ssh -n 127.0.0.1 "hostname" >/dev/null 2>&1
> done
111
222

ref:

http://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/107800/using-while-loop-to-ssh-to-multiple-servers

Change-Id: Id76b45e77612c254a3ba8a4fadabf166bef9c3a1

subject: change pxc and postgresql scenario tests to nonvoting in trove gate
commit_message:
change pxc and postgresql scenario tests to nonvoting in trove gate

These tests have become unreliable and unstable and it is now
virtually impossible to get two consistent runs of these tests given
the load on the CI infrastructure. The issue is NOT the CI
infrastructure but the fact that these tests are not
deterministic. Run on a quiet Saturday morning and they run just fine,
run them on a cloud with nested KVM and they run fine most of the
time. Run them when the CI is heavily loaded and they fail
spectacularly. The tests are not ready for prime time as we had hoped
when we made them voting earlier in the Ocata cycle. More of an effort
will be focused on stabilizing these tests in Pike.

Yet, I'm leaving the tests in as non-voting in the check and core
reviewers will look at failures to determine whether they are
introduced by the change or not and make a value judgement on whether
the subject changes should be merged or not. In the remaining short
time left for the Ocata cycle, this is likely the best we can do.

[keepalived] fix netmask for vip

For pacemaker we ensure netmask of virtual IP to 64bit for IPv6 and
32bit for IPv4. We should have feature parity in keepalived setup.[1]
The issue is that puppet picks first IP orf ifconfig output as and
interface IP. In case of IPv6 keepalived would add new IP to
interface with netmask 128 causing interface_for_ip to fail on
second puppet run.

[1] - https://github.com/openstack/puppet-tripleo/blob/master/manifests/pacemaker/haproxy_with_vip.pp

Closes-Bug: #1659309

Change-Id: Icb0c9a8d51a9bfcdc4b2caef9e52fdeb6f634cba

subject: DevStack: use Felix agent from Calico 2.0
commit_message:
DevStack: use Felix agent from Calico 2.0

To do this we have to install the Calico agent from PPA instead of building it
from source, and specifically use the calico-2.0 PPA.

The Calico agent (Felix, which by design is OpenStack-independent) was
just rewritten to be 50/50 in Go and Python; whereas previously it was
100% Python.  That means that we can't just 'pip install' it anymore.

So instead, install it from a PPA.

Change-Id: If4c78629285599f38fbdc4a096b39d1be785d15b

subject: Monkey-patch eventlet before importing urllib3
commit_message:
Monkey-patch eventlet before importing urllib3

As of the recent release of urllib3 1.20, the Calico DHCP agent was getting
this traceback on startup:

2017-01-25 11:36:10.286 3260 DEBUG etcd.client [-] Issuing read for key /calico/dhcp/v1/subnet with args {'waitIndex': 40, 'recursive': True, 'timeout': <urllib3.util.timeout.Timeout object at 0x7f2bf08a2f10>, 'wait': True} read /usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/etcd/client.py:547
[...]
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/.../eventlet/hubs/poll.py", line 115, in wait
    listener.cb(fileno)
  File "/.../eventlet/greenthread.py", line 214, in main
    result = function(*args, **kwargs)
  File "/.../networking_calico/agent/dhcp_agent.py", line 553, in loop
    super(SubnetWatcher, self).loop()
  File "/.../networking_calico/logutils.py", line 21, in wrapped
    return fn(*args, **kwargs)
  File "/.../networking_calico/etcdutils.py", line 250, in loop
    response = self.wait_for_etcd_event()
  File "/.../networking_calico/etcdutils.py", line 344, in wait_for_etcd_event
    timeout=self.etcd_timeout)
  File "/.../etcd/client.py", line 562, in read
    timeout=timeout)
  File "/.../etcd/client.py", line 820, in wrapper
    params=params, timeout=timeout)
  File "/.../etcd/client.py", line 890, in api_execute
    preload_content=False)
  File "/.../urllib3/request.py", line 66, in request
    **urlopen_kw)
  File "/.../urllib3/request.py", line 87, in request_encode_url
    return self.urlopen(method, url, **extra_kw)
  File "/.../urllib3/poolmanager.py", line 244, in urlopen
    response = conn.urlopen(method, u.request_uri, **kw)
  File "/.../urllib3/connectionpool.py", line 588, in urlopen
    conn = self._get_conn(timeout=pool_timeout)
  File "/.../urllib3/connectionpool.py", line 241, in _get_conn
    if conn and is_connection_dropped(conn):
  File "/.../urllib3/util/connection.py", line 27, in is_connection_dropped
    return bool(wait_for_read(sock, timeout=0.0))
  File "/.../urllib3/util/wait.py", line 33, in wait_for_read
    return _wait_for_io_events(socks, EVENT_READ, timeout)
  File "/.../urllib3/util/wait.py", line 22, in _wait_for_io_events
    with DefaultSelector() as selector:
  File "/.../urllib3/util/selectors.py", line 364, in __init__
    self._epoll = select.epoll()
AttributeError: 'module' object has no attribute 'epoll'
Removing descriptor: 6
2017-01-25 11:36:10.293 3260 INFO networking_calico.etcdutils [-] Stopped: aborting load of initial dump.
2017-01-25 11:36:10.293 3260 ERROR networking_calico.etcdutils [-] Unexpected IO or etcd error, triggering resync with etcd: EtcdKeyNotFound('Key not found : /calico/v1/host',).
2017-01-25 11:36:11.295 3260 INFO networking_calico.etcdutils [-] <networking_calico.agent.dhcp_agent.CalicoEtcdWatcher object at 0x7f2bf16dd750>.loop() stopped due to self.stop == True

This was because the DHCP agent was doing eventlet monkey-patching - in
particular, removing 'epoll' from the standard select module - _after_ first
importing urllib3.  This confuses urllib3's idea of which selectors are
available in the select module.

For further discussion, see https://github.com/shazow/urllib3/issues/1104.
This commit fixes by doing eventlet monkey-patching before importing urllib3.

Change-Id: I1dc823507c28824079939cc43ac1439ef4647713
